13.1 Localization QA Automation Pipeline

a. Objective

Establish a scalable, semi‚Äëautomated pipeline ensuring translated verses preserve semantic intent, calibrated difficulty, cultural neutrality, and zero answer leakage.

b. Pipeline Stages

1. Canonical Approval ‚Äì English source verse + answer finalized; answer hash derived (keccak/Poseidon) and stored.


2. Machine Pre‚Äëtranslation (MT) ‚Äì NMT service (DeepL / Google AutoML) generates baseline for target locales (e.g., es, fr, ja).


3. Human‚Äëin‚Äëthe‚ÄëLoop Refinement (HITL) ‚Äì Two independent Locale Stewards (Incubant Key Level ‚â• 3) refine MT output without seeing the answer.


4. Semantic QA Scoring ‚Äì verse:qa command computes similarity, ambiguity delta, leakage score.


5. Final Review & Approval ‚Äì Senior Steward (multi‚Äësig signer) reviews any borderline scores; merges approved locale payloads.



c. CLI Command: verse:qa

npx wl verse:qa S1-04 --canonical en --locales es,ja

Checks:

Semantic Similarity (multilingual embedding paraphrase-multilingual-mpnet-base-v2): cosine ‚â• 0.88.

Ambiguity Delta (LLM decoy variance comparison): |Œîvariance| < 0.10.

Answer Leakage (fuzzy answer / synonym match): score < 0.15.

d. QA Scorecard (JSON Output)

{
"verseId": "S1-04",
"locale": "es",
"qaReport": {
"semanticSimilarity": 0.91,
"ambiguityDelta": 0.07,
"leakageScore": 0.05,
"passed": true,
"reviewers": ["0xabc...", "0xdef..."],
"timestamp": "2025-07-21T04:30:00Z"
}
}

